<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-taylors-theorem"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Taylor's Theorem</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Taylor's theorem explains how a sufficiently differentiable function is
      approximated by its Taylor polynomial. Its proof is a repeated
      application of Rolle's theorem from <xref ref="thm-rolle"/>, so it is a
      genuine outgrowth of the Mean Value Theorem
      (<xref ref="thm-mean-value-theorem"/>).
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    Let <m>f</m> be a function with derivatives up to order <m>n</m> near
    <m>x_0</m>. The <term><m>n</m>-th Taylor polynomial</term><idx>Taylor
    polynomial</idx> of <m>f</m> at <m>x_0</m> is
    <me>
      P_n(x;x_0)=\sum_{k=0}^n \frac{f^{(k)}(x_0)}{k!}(x-x_0)^k.
    </me>
  </p>

  <p>
    We say that <m>x_0</m> is a <term>zero of multiplicity</term><idx>zero of
    multiplicity</idx> at least <m>m</m> of <m>g</m> if
    <me>
      g(x_0)=g'(x_0)=\cdots=g^{(m-1)}(x_0)=0.
    </me>
  </p>

  <lemma xml:id="lem-rolle-zero-multiplicity">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>g</m> have <m>n+1</m> derivatives on an interval <m>I</m>.
        Suppose <m>x_0 \in I</m> is a zero of multiplicity at least
        <m>n+1</m> of <m>g</m>, and suppose <m>x \in I</m> is another zero of
        <m>g</m>. Then there exists a point <m>c</m> strictly between
        <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m> such that
        <me>
          g^{(n+1)}(c)=0.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>g(x_0)=g(x)=0</m>, Rolle's theorem
        (<xref ref="thm-rolle"/>) gives a point <m>c_1</m> between
        <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m> such that <m>g'(c_1)=0</m>. Because
        <m>x_0</m> is still a zero of multiplicity at least <m>n</m> for
        <m>g'</m>, Rolle's theorem applied to <m>g'</m> on the interval with
        endpoints <m>x_0</m> and <m>c_1</m> gives a point
        <m>c_2</m> between them such that <m>g''(c_2)=0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Repeating this argument yields points
        <m>c_1,c_2,\dots,c_{n+1}</m>, each lying strictly between
        <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m>, with
        <me>
          g'(c_1)=0,\quad g''(c_2)=0,\quad \dots,\quad g^{(n+1)}(c_{n+1})=0.
        </me>
        Taking <m>c=c_{n+1}</m> completes the proof.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </lemma>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-taylor-lagrange">
    <title>Taylor's Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>f</m> has derivatives up to order <m>n+1</m> on an open
        interval containing <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m>. Then there exists a point
        <m>c</m> between <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m> such that
        <me>
          f(x)=P_n(x;x_0)+\frac{f^{(n+1)}(c)}{(n+1)!}(x-x_0)^{n+1}.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        The final term is called the <term>Lagrange remainder</term><idx>Lagrange remainder</idx>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        The case <m>x=x_0</m> is immediate, so assume <m>x \ne x_0</m>. Choose
        a constant <m>K</m> so that the function
        <me>
          g(t)=f(t)-P_n(t;x_0)-K(t-x_0)^{n+1}
        </me>
        satisfies <m>g(x)=0</m>. Since <m>P_n</m> matches the first
        <m>n</m> derivatives of <m>f</m> at <m>x_0</m>, the point
        <m>x_0</m> is a zero of multiplicity at least <m>n+1</m> of
        <m>g</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        By <xref ref="lem-rolle-zero-multiplicity"/>, there exists a point
        <m>c</m> between <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m> such that
        <m>g^{(n+1)}(c)=0</m>. But the polynomial <m>P_n</m> has zero
        <m>(n+1)</m>-st derivative, so
        <me>
          g^{(n+1)}(t)=f^{(n+1)}(t)-K(n+1)!.
        </me>
        Evaluating at <m>c</m> gives
        <me>
          0=f^{(n+1)}(c)-K(n+1)!,
        </me>
        hence
        <me>
          K=\frac{f^{(n+1)}(c)}{(n+1)!}.
        </me>
        Substituting this value of <m>K</m> into the definition of <m>g</m>
        and using <m>g(x)=0</m> yields the formula.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    When <m>n=0</m>, Taylor's theorem reduces to the Mean Value Theorem. So it
    is best viewed as a higher-order version of the same idea.
  </p>

  <p>
    There is another useful expression for the remainder term. It is
    especially well suited to error estimates and to proving power-series
    expansions of familiar functions.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-integration-by-parts-special-case">
    <title>Integration by Parts</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Assume the basic properties of the definite integral. If
        <m>u,v \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> are continuously differentiable, then
        <me>
          \int_a^b u'(t)v(t)\,dt
          =
          u(b)v(b)-u(a)v(a)-\int_a^b u(t)v'(t)\,dt.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        By the product rule
        (<xref ref="prop-derivative-sum-product-rules"/>),
        <me>
          (uv)'(t)=u'(t)v(t)+u(t)v'(t).
        </me>
        Integrating both sides from <m>a</m> to <m>b</m> and applying
        <xref ref="cor-newton-leibniz-special-case"/> to the function
        <m>uv</m>, we get
        <me>
          u(b)v(b)-u(a)v(a)
          =
          \int_a^b u'(t)v(t)\,dt + \int_a^b u(t)v'(t)\,dt.
        </me>
        Rearranging gives the result.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    This is a convenient special case tailored to the present argument. A more
    general integration-by-parts formula, together with a change-of-variables
    theorem, appears later in the integration chapter; see
    <xref ref="prop-integration-by-parts"/> and
    <xref ref="thm-change-of-variables"/>.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-taylor-integral-remainder">
    <title>Taylor's Theorem with Integral Remainder</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Assume the basic properties of the definite integral. Suppose
        <m>f \in C^{n+1}(I)</m>, where <m>I</m> is a closed interval with
        endpoints <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m>. Then
        <me>
          f(x)=P_n(x;x_0)+\frac{1}{n!}\int_{x_0}^x f^{(n+1)}(t)(x-t)^n\,dt.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        The final term is called the <term>integral form of the
        remainder</term><idx>integral remainder</idx>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        If <m>x=x_0</m>, the formula is immediate. If <m>x \lt x_0</m>, then
        the same argument applied on the interval with endpoints
        <m>x</m> and <m>x_0</m> gives the result after reversing the limits of
        integration. So it is enough to treat the case <m>x_0 \lt x</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For each <m>k=0,1,\dots,n</m>, define
        <me>
          R_k(x;x_0):=\frac{1}{k!}\int_{x_0}^x f^{(k+1)}(t)(x-t)^k\,dt.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        When <m>k=0</m>, the Newton-Leibniz formula
        (<xref ref="cor-newton-leibniz-special-case"/>) gives
        <me>
          R_0(x;x_0)=\int_{x_0}^x f'(t)\,dt = f(x)-f(x_0).
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Now let <m>1 \le k \le n</m>. Apply
        <xref ref="prop-integration-by-parts-special-case"/> with
        <me>
          u(t)=f^{(k)}(t)
          \qquad \text{and} \qquad
          v(t)=\frac{(x-t)^k}{k!}.
        </me>
        Then <m>u'(t)=f^{(k+1)}(t)</m> and
        <me>
          v'(t)=-\frac{(x-t)^{k-1}}{(k-1)!}.
        </me>
        Therefore
        <me>
          R_k(x;x_0)
          =
          \left[\frac{f^{(k)}(t)(x-t)^k}{k!}\right]_{t=x_0}^{t=x}
          +
          \frac{1}{(k-1)!}\int_{x_0}^x f^{(k)}(t)(x-t)^{k-1}\,dt.
        </me>
        Since <m>(x-x)^k=0</m>, this becomes
        <me>
          R_k(x;x_0)
          =
          -\frac{f^{(k)}(x_0)}{k!}(x-x_0)^k + R_{k-1}(x;x_0).
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Starting from <m>R_0(x;x_0)=f(x)-f(x_0)</m> and applying the recurrence
        successively for <m>k=1,2,\dots,n</m>, we obtain
        <me>
          R_n(x;x_0)
          =
          f(x)-\sum_{k=0}^n \frac{f^{(k)}(x_0)}{k!}(x-x_0)^k
          =
          f(x)-P_n(x;x_0).
        </me>
        Rearranging gives the desired formula.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <corollary xml:id="cor-taylor-remainder-goes-to-zero">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>f</m> has derivatives of all orders on an interval
        containing <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m>. If there exists a constant
        <m>M&gt;0</m> such that
        <me>
          |f^{(n)}(t)| \le M
        </me>
        for every <m>n \ge 1</m> and every <m>t</m> between <m>x_0</m> and
        <m>x</m>, then the Taylor series of <m>f</m> at <m>x_0</m> converges
        to <m>f(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        By Taylor's theorem,
        <me>
          f(x)-P_n(x;x_0)
          =
          \frac{f^{(n+1)}(c_n)}{(n+1)!}(x-x_0)^{n+1}
        </me>
        for some point <m>c_n</m> between <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m>. Hence
        <me>
          |f(x)-P_n(x;x_0)|
          \le
          M\frac{|x-x_0|^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}.
        </me>
        By <xref ref="prop-growth-comparison-basic-sequences"/>,
        <m>|x-x_0|^{n+1}/(n+1)! \to 0</m>. Therefore
        <m>P_n(x;x_0)\to f(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </corollary>

  <example xml:id="eg-taylor-exp">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Assume the standard calculus facts that <m>(e^x)'=e^x</m> and that
        <m>e^x</m> is continuous. Fix <m>x_0 \in \R</m>, and choose a closed
        interval containing both <m>0</m> and <m>x_0</m>. By the Extreme Value
        Theorem (<xref ref="thm-extreme-value-theorem"/>), <m>e^x</m> is
        bounded there by some constant <m>M</m>. Since every derivative of
        <m>e^x</m> is again <m>e^x</m>, the previous corollary gives
        <me>
          e^{x_0}=\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x_0^n}{n!}.
        </me>
        Because <m>x_0</m> was arbitrary, the exponential function is analytic
        on all of <m>\R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-binomial-series">
    <title>Binomial Series</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each <m>\alpha \in \R</m>,
        <me>
          (1+x)^\alpha
          =
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty \binom{\alpha}{n}x^n
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1,
        </me>
        where
        <me>
          \binom{\alpha}{n}
          =
          \frac{\alpha(\alpha-1)\cdots(\alpha-n+1)}{n!}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        We omit the proof. The ratio test shows that the series has radius of
        convergence <m>1</m>, and term-by-term differentiation leads to a
        differential equation satisfied by both sides.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-binomial-series-sqrt">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Taking <m>\alpha=1/2</m> gives
        <me>
          \sqrt{1+x}
          =
          1+\frac12x-\frac18x^2+\frac1{16}x^3-\frac{5}{128}x^4+\cdots
          \qquad \text{for } |x|&lt;1.
        </me>
        So <m>\sqrt{1+x}</m> is analytic at <m>0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

</section>
